    "long_instructions": "## Do This:\r\n\r\n1. Run your code and observe the outcome. \r\n    - *Tip: Make sure to run the program with both \"grass\" and \"flower\" for user inputs.*\r\n2. *Discuss: If we want the program to do one thing when the user enters \"grass\" and something **else** when the user enters \"flower\", what might be missing from the conditional statement?*\r\n3. Add the missing `else` statement with code to make the `Painter` plant a flower of your choice.\r\n4. Run your code again to make sure the `Painter` plants a flower.\r\n",
    "start_sources": {
      "files": {
        "0": {
          "id": "0",
          "name": "main.py",
          "language": "py",
          "contents": "from neighborhood import Painter\n\n# Create a new Painter object\ntalia = Painter()\n\n# Define a function that takes in user input\ndef flower_or_grass():\n  # Declare variable for user input\n  what_to_plant = input(\"Do you want to plant grass or a flower? \")\n  \n  # Set the amount of paint the Painter has\n  talia.set_paint(5)\n\n  # While painter has paint, if user input is \"green\" then move, add dirt, plant grass, and move\n  # Else move, add dirt, plant flower, and move\n  while talia.has_paint():   \n    if what_to_plant == \"grass\":\n      talia.paint(\"saddlebrown\")\n      talia.move()\n      talia.paint(\"saddlebrown\")\n      talia.move()\n      talia.paint(\"green\")\n      talia.move()\n      talia.paint(\"saddlebrown\")\n      talia.move()\n      talia.paint(\"saddlebrown\")\n    # ADD MISSING CODE HERE\n\n\n# Call your function here\nflower_or_grass()",
          "folderId": "0",
          "active": true,
          "open": true
        }
      },
